,"id":"58007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58007"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. She reports mild exertional dyspnoea but is otherwise well. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Cardiac examination reveals a grade 3/6 murmur heard best at the cardiac apex (left 5th intercostal space, mid-clavicular line) that radiates to the axilla. The murmur is present throughout systole and increases in intensity during expiration. The rest of the cardiovascular examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aortic stenosis","Mitral stenosis","Aortic regurgitation","Tricuspid regurgitation","Mitral regurgitation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a cardiac murmur with specific characteristics that help identify its origin. \u003Cstrong\u003EMitral regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E typically produces a pansystolic murmur best heard at the cardiac apex (left 5th intercostal space, mid-clavicular line) that radiates to the axilla. The murmur typically increases with manoeuvres that increase afterload, such as expiration, as this increases the regurgitant flow across the incompetent mitral valve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically produces an ejection systolic murmur best heard at the right upper sternal edge that radiates to the carotids. It typically increases with expiration and does not radiate to the axilla.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETricuspid regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E produces a pansystolic murmur best heard at the left lower sternal edge that increases with inspiration (not expiration) due to increased right ventricular filling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E produces an early diastolic murmur best heard at the left sternal edge with the patient sitting forward in expiration. It does not produce a systolic murmur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitral stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E produces a mid-diastolic murmur best heard at the apex with the patient in the left lateral position. It does not produce a systolic murmur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe characteristics of cardiac murmurs - including timing in the cardiac cycle, location of maximal intensity, radiation pattern, and response to physiological manoeuvres - are crucial in determining their origin. Understanding these patterns helps in making accurate clinical diagnoses of valvular heart disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mitral regurgitation classically produces a pansystolic murmur best heard at the cardiac apex that radiates to the axilla","Increased left ventricular afterload (as occurs during expiration) worsens mitral regurgitation","The timing, location and radiation of cardiac murmurs are key features in distinguishing their origin"],"references":["Talley and O\u0027Connor\u0027s Clinical Examination 9th edition."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43466"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14690"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43466"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T19:44:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T19:45:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7383"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58007"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonym